introduction, callouts, and CTA sections. I'm also addressing the\n...\n\n=== FORENSIC CRITIQUE 3 (pos 1334557) ===\nantly expanded the critique and improvement plan to include the granular \"minor details\" a new team member needs to master our specific brand of forensic storytelling. I have successfully updated the Forensic Critique and Strategic Outline . Key updates made: Narrative Headers: Removed stats from H2/H3 headings (e.g., \"The 40% surge\" became \"The acquisition trap\") to allow the story to unfold naturally within the text. Expanded Critique: Added a \"Linguistically Soft\" analysis and the \"Post-Mortem\" section to help a new employee understand the high stakes of our editorial voice. Bridge &amp; Logic Details: Included instructions on the \"Internal Bridge\" to ensure paragraphs don't feel like independent silos. Math Clarity: Explicitly showed the $117,000 calculation logic in the outline to serve as a placeholder for the draft. How would you like to proceed? Should we move to Phase 5 and generate the full draft based on this outline? You said But I told you I kind of don't like using \"Trap\" and \"Tax\" needlessly anymore. T The Content Architect Custom Gem Show thinking Revising Terminology Choices Okay, I'm currently focused on the document update. I'm carefully reviewing the \"Master Session Rules and Content SOPs\" document, and its strategic plan, to eliminate the phrases \"Trap\" and \"Tax\". I'm aiming for clarity without those potentially negative connotations. This requires some careful word choices. Refining Word Substitutions I've got a plan for this SOP and Strategic plan update. In the SOP, I'll explicitly mention avoiding \"Trap\" and \"Tax,\" instead suggesting \"economic ceiling,\" or \"management burden,\" under \"Prohibited Jargon.\" I'll also reiterate the edgy approach should still be provocative, and if these terms feel negative, to avoid them! I'll update the Strategic Plan, checking for those terms, and update the outlin