roper capitalization, ensuring the tone remains focused on street-level realism for a busy founder.\nArticle: Freelance Administrative Assistant Guide\nMar 10, 1:19 PM\nOpen\nI have completed the final draft of the article. It follows your\n3x3 premise flow\n, adheres to the\n4-6 sentence paragraph rule\n, and integrates all research findings into a cohesive, street-level argument.\nSummary of the Build:\nKeyword Optimization:\nPlaced \"freelance administrative assistant\" in the H1, first paragraph, one H2, and Conclusion.\nBridge Protocol:\nEvery paragraph leads with a transition (e.g., \"Furthermore,\" \"To begin with,\" \"Worse,\" \"Consequently\").\nPlain English:\nReplaced all jargon with street-level terms like \"hiring ceiling,\" \"management burden,\" and \"growth trap.\"\nSOP Consistency:\nEach H3 contains exactly two paragraphs, and each H2 ends with a provocative blockquote callout.\nHow would you like to proceed with the next article or the updated SOP review?\nYou said\nThis sounds way too similar an intro to my other work. Make this intro paragraph edgy.\nT\nThe Content Architect\nCustom Gem\nShow thinking\nThe Content Architect said\nI have rewritten the introduction of the article in\nCanvas\nto adopt a sharper, more provocative tone that highlights the \"hidden war\" founders fight against their own inboxes. The new opening focuses on the failure of hustle culture and the high cost of becoming a full-time supervisor for gig workers.\nYou said\nI have been clear about needlessly putting bold font. This shouldn't happen even for keywords!\nT\nThe Content Architect\nCustom Gem\nShow thinking\nThe Content Architect said\nI apologize for the oversight. I have updated the session rules to strictly forbid bolding in the body text, including SEO keywords. I have also corrected the final draft of the freelance administrative assistant guide to remove all bolding and fixed a leftover keyword from the previous article in the conclusion.\nI have updated the\nS