ustomGPT flagged them as \"omissions\" and asked if they were intentional. It couldn't tell the difference between a deliberate choice and an accidental deletion.\n+160 \n+161 **The lesson:** The editor skill must recognize deliberate structural changes as valid editorial decisions, not anomalies to question. Specific signals:\n+162 - If a paragraph is shorter than the 2x4-6 minimum, don't ask \"did you mean to cut this?\" — ask \"do you want me to expand this or is the compression intentional?\"\n+163 - If a story/anecdote is removed, don't flag it — the author's compression instincts are valid\n+164 - Tiny's cuts are almost always deliberate: he is killing darlings efficiently\n+165 \n+166 ---\n+167 \n+168 ### FAILURE 3: Tone Miscalibration\n+169 **What happened:** The CustomGPT kept proposing \"ultimate guide\" framing (soft, helpful) when Tiny wanted contrarian positioning (strategic, challenging). Even after explicit pushback, it oscillated between the two registers.\n+170 \n+171 **The lesson:** When Tiny says \"I don't like this direction,\" the skill must immediately abandon that register entirely and propose alternatives in a different voice. Do not:\n+172 - Revise the same idea with minor word swaps\n+173 - Explain why the original was good\n+174 - Offer alternatives in the same rejected tone\n+175 \n+176 ---\n+177 \n+178 ### FAILURE 4: Confirmation Bias Blindness\n+179 **What happened:** The CustomGPT proposed angles Tiny hadn't considered, but framed them as validation rather than expansion. It reinforced what it thought Tiny wanted to hear rather than genuinely stress-testing the thesis.\n+180 \n+181 **The lesson:** The skill must actively surface the counter-position before drafting. Specifically:\n+182 - Before any H2 structure is finalized, state the strongest argument AGAINST the article's thesis\n+183 - If the article argues \"freelancers are a risk,\" the editor must articulate \"when freelancers are actually the right choice\"\n+184 - This isn't h