{"type":"message","id":"1c3ded96","parentId":"ebe946f2","timestamp":"2026-04-01T14:50:53.519Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Yes — and that's exactly right.\n\nThe 2x4-6 was a **scaffolding tool**, not a law of physics. It forced the AI to stop writing thin, 2-sentence paragraphs that felt like bullet points in disguise. But:\n\n**Why the rules break down in practice:**\n\n- Strict H3 = exactly 2 paragraphs → you end up forcing content into a structural mold that doesn't fit the idea\n- Strict 4-6 sentences per paragraph → sometimes an idea needs 2 sentences to land cleanly, or 8 to breathe\n- The GPT followed the rules **mechanically** — Tiny breaks them **strategically**\n\n**What you're doing instead:**\n\n- Shorter paragraphs where the idea hits clean and doesn't need setup\n- Longer paragraphs where the argument builds and compounds\n- The rhythm is now **yours** — you're not forcing content into a template, you're using the template to train the instinct and then moving past it\n\n**The meta-point:** The custom GPT needed the rules because it has no internal bar for \"this is enough.\" Tiny doesn't need the rules because he **internalized the principle** — he knows when a paragraph earns its length and when it's just padding. Rules are for training; the trained eye transcends them.\n\nThis is the difference between **knowing the rules of writing** and **being a writer**. 🌙"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":40021,"output":548,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":40569,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775055053518}}
