{"type":"message","id":"d86efa6a","parentId":"35aea0b1","timestamp":"2026-04-01T15:04:38.961Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You're right to check. I missed several things. Here's the full accounting:\n\n**Already had:**\n- Phase enforcement (H1 → H2 → H3 → Canvas → Draft, no auto-generation)\n- Narrative flow + transitions\n- No jargon, no needless caps, no \"trap/tax\" terminology\n- Paragraph independence (distinct beats, not rephrasing)\n- Platform name-drops in intro (Upwork, Fiverr)\n- Avoiding overlap with existing articles\n- \"Hiring revolving door\" lesson (comprehension ≠ vocabulary)\n- Hallucination prevention\n\n**Just captured now — things I missed:**\n\n1. **Keywords: NO bold in body text**\n   \"I have been clear about needlessly putting bold font. **This shouldn't happen even for keywords!**\" — Keywords appear naturally in text, never bolded.\n\n2. **Meta info + callouts + FAQs at end**\n   \"Update the meta info, callouts, to match the article. The FAQs are perfect.\" — Final housekeeping step after draft is done.\n\n3. **The \"suspend the win\" intro approach**\n   \"start without giving away the solution or maybe even highlight the wins of such platforms while leaving an air of mystery that we will reveal how they fail.\" — Acknowledge the appeal first, then reveal the failure. Not \"here's why X is bad\" — more \"here's why X seems great, and here's what's actually happening.\"\n\n4. **\"Edgy\" requirement for intro**\n   Tiny rejected an intro as \"too similar to my other work\" — the voice needs to feel distinct, not templated.\n\n5. **Blockquote callouts at end of each H2**\n   Each section ends with a provocative blockquote — captured, was in my earlier notes but forgot to include in the formal update.\n\n6. **Keyword placement rule**\n   Primary keyword: H1 + first paragraph + one H2 + Conclusion. Secondary keywords woven through H3 body text.\n\n7. **Link to previous articles, don't re-explain**\n   \"Emb