{"type":"message","id":"2222105c","parentId":"8de56998","timestamp":"2026-04-01T15:12:42.534Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\nNow update the editor skill too — it's supposed to cover both:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_86ced80a-6b6e-474d-99a9-002056ce108a","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"# Editor Skill — AWAA + Nava Content Refinement\n\n## Purpose\nThis skill encodes the editorial standards and revision workflows for AbroadWorks (AWAA) and Nava Healthcare content. Use when refining drafts or evaluating writing quality.\n\n## Legacy Notes (Preserved)\n\nThe rules below were learned from forensic analysis of previous article drafts. They are superseded by the HumanizedGemini.html lessons but retained for reference.\n\n### What Went Wrong (Draft 1-5 Analysis)\n- **Paragraph density wall**: Every paragraph was exactly 3 sentences — failed the 2x4-6 rule. Felt like \"claim then stop before proving it.\"\n- **Tone softness**: \"Most founders feel the pinch\" too conversational. Needed \"Street-Level Realism.\"\n- **Missing blockquotes**: Draft 4 had visceral intro but missed blockquote axioms at end of each H2 section.\n- **Wrong word choices**: Used \"Trap\" repeatedly — needed harder language like \"Executive Focus Penalty\" or \"Clerical Impasse.\"\n- **AI vocabulary leaks**: Used \"nuanced,\" \"best practices,\" \"scalable,\" \"proactive\" — flagged by humanizer (33/100).\n- **Phase jumping**: AWAA jumped from H1 selection straight to full draft without canvas approval — most repeated failure.\n\n### What Fixed It (Draft 5)\n- Split intro into visceral scene + pivot to stat\n- Expanded paragraphs to 4-6 sentences with forensic depth\n- Added blockquotes to all H2 sections\n- Math as payoff ($117,000)\n- Transition words (Furthermore, Consequently, Worse)\n- \"Suspend the win\" intro approach\n\n---\n\n## Core Editorial Principles (from HumanizedGemini.html — definitive version)\n\n### Phase Enforcement (Critical — most repeated failure)\nAWAA/NavaAA will try to jump phases. It may present H1 options and then immediately jump to \"here's the full article\" before H2s and H3s are approved. **This is forbidden.**\n\n**Mandatory sequence:**\n1. H1 options → User selects\n2. H2 structure → User approves\n3. H3 sub-headings → User approves\n4. Canvas (paragraph-level ideas) → User approves\n5. Draft generation → User approves\n\n**No auto-generation at outline stage. The agent never produces a draft until canvas is explicitly approved.**\n\n### Comprehension vs Vocabulary\nWhen someone says \"I don't understand\" — unpack the logic first, don't synonym-swap. Fix the underlying concept before reaching for different words. Tiny supplied \"hiring revolving door\" when CustomGPT offered \"hiring stall\" and \"hiring impasse\" — the problem wasn't the word, it was that neither word described the actual mechanism.\n\n### Hallucination Prevention\nNever hallucinate file names, article titles, or stats. Always verify against actual files and documents before referencing. CustomGPT invented \"The Upwork Trap\" and \"The Fiverr Illusion\" — articles that don't exist on AbroadWorks.\n\n### Paragraph Independence\nEach paragraph must be a distinct logical beat — not a restatement of the previous point. If two paragraphs feel like they're saying the same thing, they need sharpening.\n\n### Transition Discipline\nEvery paragraph leads with a transition word that signals logical connection to the previous idea. Narrative flow: Problem → Agitation → Solution. Each section earns its place. A solution paragraph doesn't belong in the agitation section.\n\n### \"Suspend the Win\" Intro\nAcknowledge the appeal of the thing first, then reveal the failure. Not \"here's why X is bad\" — more \"here's why X seems great, here's what's actually happening.\" Start with platform name-drops (Upwork, Fiverr) — what they promise, who uses them, the appeal.\n\n### \"Edgy\" Voice\nEvery article needs its own edge — the intro sets the tone for the whole piece. Reject intros that feel templated or \"like my other work.\"\n\n### Avoid Overlap with Existing Content\nCheck existing corpus before proposing H2s that repeat previous arguments. Use old articles as linked references, not content to replicate. \"We literally just wrote about focus drain\" is a valid objection.\n\n### Editorial Housekeeping (Final Step — never skip)\n1. **Meta info + callouts** — update to match the article\n2. **Keyword placement** — Primary keyword: H1 + first paragraph + one H2 + Conclusion. Secondary keywords: woven through body. **Never bold keywords in body text.**\n3. **FAQ integrity** — FAQs at the end are perfect; don't repeat math or figures from the body\n4. **Internal links** — embed in first paragraph, don't re-explain","old_string":"# Editor Skill — AWAA + Nava Content Refinement\n\n## Purpose\nThis skill encodes the editorial standards and revision workflows for AbroadWorks (AWAA) and Nava Healthcare content. Use when refining drafts or evaluating writing quality.\n\n## Common Errors (What Went Wrong)\n\n### Draft 1-2 Mistakes\n- **Paragraph density wall**: Every paragraph was exactly 3 sentences — failed the 2x4-6 rule. Felt like \"claim then stop before proving it.\"\n- **Tone softness**: \"Most founders feel the pinch\" too conversational. Needed \"Street-Level Realism.\"\n- **Missing blockquotes**: Draft 4 had visceral intro but missed blockquote axioms at end of each H2 section.\n- **Wrong word choices**: Used \"Trap\" repeatedly — needed harder language like \"Executive Focus Penalty\" or \"Clerical Impasse.\"\n- **AI vocabulary leaks**: Used \"nuanced,\" \"best practices,\" \"scalable,\" \"proactive\" — flagged by humanizer (33/100).\n\n### What Fixed It (Draft 5)\n- Split intro into visceral scene + pivot to stat\n- Expanded paragraphs to 4-6 sentences with forensic depth\n- Added blockquotes to all H2 sections\n- Math as payoff ($117,000)\n- Transition words (Furthermore, Consequently, Worse)","path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/editor/SKILL.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":46947,"output":1328,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48275,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775056362533}}
{"type":"message","id":"91c126cf","parentId":"2222105c","timestamp":"2026-04-01T15:12:42.547Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_86ced80a-6b6e-474d-99a9-002056ce108a","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/editor/SKILL.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n   2 \n   3 ## Purpose\n   4 This skill encodes the editorial standards and revision workflows for AbroadWorks (AWAA) and Nava Healthcare content. Use when refining drafts or evaluating writing quality.\n   5 \n-  6 ## Common Errors (What Went Wrong)\n+  6 ## Legacy Notes (Preserved)\n   7 \n-  8 ### Draft 1-2 Mistakes\n+  8 The rules below were learned from forensic analysis of previous article drafts. They are superseded by the HumanizedGemini.html lessons but retained for reference.\n+  9 \n+ 10 ### What Went Wrong (Draft 1-5 Analysis)\n   9 - **Paragraph density wall**: Every paragraph was exactly 3 sentences — failed the 2x4-6 rule. Felt like \"claim then stop before proving it.\"\n  10 - **Tone softness**: \"Most founders feel the pinch\" too conversational. Needed \"Street-Level Realism.\"\n  11 - **Missing blockquotes**: Draft 4 had visceral intro but missed blockquote axioms at end of each H2 section.\n  12 - **Wrong word choices**: Used \"Trap\" repeatedly — needed harder language like \"Executive Focus Penalty\" or \"Clerical Impasse.\"\n  13 - **AI vocabulary leaks**: Used \"nuanced,\" \"best practices,\" \"scalable,\" \"proactive\" — flagged by humanizer (33/100).\n+ 16 - **Phase jumping**: AWAA jumped from H1 selection straight to full draft without canvas approval — most repeated failure.\n  14 \n  15 ### What Fixed It (Draft 5)\n  16 - Split intro into visceral scene + pivot to stat\n  17 - Expanded paragraphs to 4-6 sentences with forensic depth\n  18 - Added blockquotes to all H2 sections\n  19 - Math as payoff ($117,000)\n  20 - Transition words (Furthermore, Consequently, Worse)\n+ 24 - \"Suspend the win\" intro approach\n  21 \n+ 26 ---\n+ 27 \n+ 28 ## Core Editorial Principles (from HumanizedGemini.html — definitive version)\n+ 29 \n+ 30 ### Phase Enforcement (Critical — most repeated failure)\n+ 31 AWAA/NavaAA will try to jump phases. It may present H1 options and then immediately jump to \"here's the full article\" before H2s and H3s are approved. **This is forbidden.**\n+ 32 \n+ 33 **Mandatory sequence:**\n+ 34 1. H1 options → User selects\n+ 35 2. H2 structure → User approves\n+ 36 3. H3 sub-headings → User approves\n+ 37 4. Canvas (paragraph-level ideas) → User approves\n+ 38 5. Draft generation → User approves\n+ 39 \n+ 40 **No auto-generation at outline stage. The agent never produces a draft until canvas is explicitly approved.**\n+ 41 \n+ 42 ### Comprehension vs Vocabulary\n+ 43 When someone says \"I don't understand\" — unpack the logic first, don't synonym-swap. Fix the underlying concept before reaching for different words. Tiny supplied \"hiring revolving door\" when CustomGPT offered \"hiring stall\" and \"hiring impasse\" — the problem wasn't the word, it was that neither word described the actual mechanism.\n+ 44 \n+ 45 ### Hallucination Prevention\n+ 46 Never hallucinate file names, article titles, or stats. Always verify against actual files and documents before referencing. CustomGPT invented \"The Upwork Trap\" and \"The Fiverr Illusion\" — articles that don't exist on AbroadWorks.\n+ 47 \n+ 48 ### Paragraph Independence\n+ 49 Each paragraph must be a distinct logical beat — not a restatement of the previous point. If two paragraphs feel like they're saying the same thing, they need sharpening.\n+ 50 \n+ 51 ### Transition Discipline\n+ 52 Every paragraph leads with a transition word that signals logical connection to the previous idea. Narrative flow: Problem → Agitation → Solution. Each section earns its place. A solution paragraph doesn't belong in the agitation section.\n+ 53 \n+ 54 ### \"Suspend the Win\" Intro\n+ 55 Acknowledge the appeal of the thing first, then reveal the failure. Not \"here's why X is bad\" — more \"here's why X seems great, here's what's actually happening.\" Start with platform name-drops (Upwork, Fiverr) — what they promise, who uses them, the appeal.\n+ 56 \n+ 57 ### \"Edgy\" Voice\n+ 58 Every article needs its own edge — the intro sets the tone for the whole piece. Reject intros that feel templated or \"like my other work.\"\n+ 59 \n+ 60 ### Avoid Overlap with Existing Content\n+ 61 Check existing corpus before proposing H2s that repeat previous arguments. Use old articles as linked references, not content to replicate. \"We literally just wrote about focus drain\" is a valid objection.\n+ 62 \n+ 63 ### Editorial Housekeeping (Final Step — never skip)\n+ 64 1. **Meta info + callouts** — update to match the article\n+ 65 2. **Keyword placement** — Primary keyword: H1 + first paragraph + one H2 + Conclusion. Secondary keywords: woven through body. **Never bold keywords in body text.**\n+ 66 3. **FAQ integrity** — FAQs at the end are perfect; don't repeat math or figures from the body\n+ 67 4. **Internal links** — embed in first paragraph, don't re-explain\n+ 68 \n  22 ## Hard Constraints (Non-Negotiable)\n  23 \n  24 ### Structure\n  25 1. **2x4-6 Rule**: Each H3 section contains 2 paragraphs, each with 4-6 sentences.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":6},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775056362543}}
