uate-level reading. Sentences are too long and complex. Needs simpler structure throughout.\\n\\n**2. Proportionality (C3) — FAIL — severity 0.67**\\nEvidence (weak) can't support the claims being made (extraordinary). The article says things like \\\"9 out of 10 sales teams will miss their goals\\\" and \\\"61% of B2B buyers purchase solutions for problems they didn't know they had\\\" — big stats, but the evidence backing them is thin. Either cite stronger sources or dial the claim language back.\\n\\n**3. Logical Flow (B2) — FAIL — severity 0.85**\\nFragmented connections between sentences. Many paragraphs read as lists of assertions rather than connected argument. The \\\"bridge protocol\\\" rule (transition words on every paragraph lead) is being violated throughout. This is the most actionable fix — it's mechanical, not conceptual.\\n\\n**4. Thesis Clarity (B1) — Warning**\\nMultiple competing thesis candidates detected. The opening paragraph makes several large claims (performance gap, $15T market, 40% CAC increase) without landing on one clear primary thesis. The reader doesn't know what the article is *about* until partway through.\\n\\n**5. Linguistic Integrity (A1) — Warning (55 errors)**\\nMechanical errors: spacing after commas (\\\"7,0\\\" instead of \\\"7, 0\\\"), missing spaces after periods (\\\"f.a\\\", \\\"o.c\\\"). Easy fixes but pervasive — likely from copy-pasting from different sources.\\n\\n**6. Argumentative Rigor (C2) — Warning**\\nAppeal-to-authority fallacy detected. The article cites \\\"research indicates\\\" and unnamed studies without linking to t\n\n=== Line 361 ===\n{\"type\": \"message\", \"id\": \"ef055977\", \"parentId\": \"87ea8653\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-01T15:29:07.399Z\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"The tool is right about the real problems. But I have some pushback on the overall framing.\\n\\n**Where the report is correct:**\\n\\nThe **logical flow** failure is real. Some paragraphs are just assertion stacks — \\\"this happens, then this happens, then this happens\\\" — without bridges between them. The transition discipline Tiny preaches (and that I encoded in the editor skill) is inconsistently applied in this article. Fixable, but it's the most legitimate structural complaint.\\n\\nThe **evidence-inline problem** is also real. The article links to sources, but the visible claims read as bald assertions that a reader can't evaluate without clicking. For investor-grade content, the evidence should be *visible*, not hidden behind a hyperlink. That's a rewrite decision, not a copyedit.\\n\\n**Where I push back:**\\n\\nThe **readability verdict (FKGL 12.6)** is the wrong benchmark for this content. This isn't a lifestyle blog. It's B2B strategic content aimed at founders who parse dense material daily. FKGL 12.6 is normal for Harvard Business Review, a16z posts, and similar investor-grade publications. TinyQE's blog benchmark (7.0–10.0) is calibrated for mass-consumer content. If there's no B2B strategic format profile in the config, the tool is comparing this article to the wrong reference class.\\n\\n**The proportionality verdict** is partially right but overstated. \\\"9 out of 10 teams will miss goals\\\" is a sourced claim (it links to optif.ai). The issue is it's *孤立地* (isolated) — no context about sample size, methodology, or date. Strengthen the inline framing and the verdict improves without changing the content.\\n\\n**My overall read:**\\n\\nThis is a solid 65–70% article that Tiny manually improved from a lower baseline. The voice is consistent, the structure is sound, the argument flows. The three mec\n\n=== Line 362 ===\n{\"type\": \"compaction\", \"id\": \"2e2e5a4c\", \"parentId\": \"ef055977\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-01T15:29:07.440Z\", \"summary\": \"## Goal\\nMorning routine execution: brief Tiny on current status, identify pending tasks, ask what he needs done today.\\n\\n## Decisions\\n- **Morning routin