{"type":"message","id":"c95df4d8","parentId":"98e76996","timestamp":"2026-04-01T15:35:28.521Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_3ca2cdef-0669-4a25-9786-389f633ec5ed","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The tool is right about the real problems. But I have some pushback on the overall framing.\n\n**Where the report is correct:**\n\nThe **logical flow** failure is real. Some paragraphs are just assertion stacks — \"this happens, then this happens, then this happens\" — without bridges between them. The transition discipline Tiny preaches (and that I encoded in the editor skill) is inconsistently applied in this article. Fixable, but it's the most legitimate structural complaint.\n\nThe **evidence-inline problem** is also real. The article links to sources, but the visible claims read as bald assertions that a reader can't evaluate without clicking. For investor-grade content, the evidence should be *visible*, not hidden behind a hyperlink. That's a rewrite decision, not a copyedit.\n\n**Where I push back:**\n\nThe **readability verdict (FKGL 12.6)** is the wrong benchmark for this content. This isn't a lifestyle blog. It's B2B strategic content aimed at founders who parse dense material daily. FKGL 12.6 is normal for Harvard Business Review, a16z posts, and similar investor-grade publications. TinyQE's blog benchmark (7.0–10.0) is calibrated for mass-consumer content. If there's no B2B strategic format profile in the config, the tool is comparing this article to the wrong reference class.\n\n**The proportionality verdict** is partially right but overstated. \"9 out of 10 teams will miss goals\" is a sourced claim (it links to optif.ai). The issue is it's *孤立地* (isolated) — no context about sample size, methodology, or date. Strengthen the inline framing and the verdict improves without changing the content.\n\n**My overall read:**\n\nThis is a solid 65–70% article that Tiny manually improved from a lower baseline. The voice is consistent, the structure is sound, the argument flows. The three mechanical issues (flow, evidence visibility, comma spacing) are all fixable in one editing pass. The proportionality concern is the only one that might require a real rethink — either dial the claims back or bring the sources more visibly into the text.\n\n**What I'd tell TinyQE:** The overall score of 0.605 feels low for what this actually is. The tool is being справедлив (fair) about the problems but isn't accounting for format appropriateness. A B2B strategic brief with this voice and structure, targeting this audience, scores higher in practice than the raw numbers suggest."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":64,"aggregated":"The tool is right about the real problems. But I have some pushback on the overall framing.\n\n**Where the report is correct:**\n\nThe **logical flow** failure is real. Some paragraphs are just assertion stacks — \"this happens, then this happens, then this happens\" — without bridges between them. The transition discipline Tiny preaches (and that I encoded in the editor skill) is inconsistently applied in this article. Fixable, but it's the most legitimate structural complaint.\n\nThe **evidence-inline problem** is also real. The article links to sources, but the visible claims read as bald assertions that a reader can't evaluate without clicking. For investor-grade content, the evidence should be *visible*, not hidden behind a hyperlink. That's a rewrite decision, not a copyedit.\n\n**Where I push back:**\n\nThe **readability verdict (FKGL 12.6)** is the wrong benchmark for this content. This isn't a lifestyle blog. It's B2B strategic content aimed at founders who parse dense material daily. FKGL 12.6 is normal for Harvard Business Review, a16z posts, and similar investor-grade publications. TinyQE's blog benchmark (7.0–10.0) is calibrated for mass-consumer content. If there's no B2B strategic format profile in the config, the tool is comparing this article to the wrong reference class.\n\n**The proportionality verdict** is partially right but overstated. \"9 out of 10 teams will miss goals\" is a sourced claim (it links to optif.ai). The issue is it's *孤立地* (isolated) — no context about sample size, methodology, or date. Strengthen the inline framing and the verdict improves without changing the content.\n\n**My overall read:**\n\nThis is a solid 65–70% article that Tiny manually improved from a lower baseline. The voice is consistent, the structure is sound, the argument flows. The three mechanical issues (flow, evidence visibility, comma spacing) are all fixable in one editing pass. The proportionality concern is the only one that might require a real rethink — either dial the claims back or bring the sources more visibly into the text.\n\n**What I'd tell TinyQE:** The overall score of 0.605 feels low for what this actually is. The tool is being справедлив (fair) about the problems but isn't accounting for format appropriateness. A B2B strategic brief with this voice and structure, targeting this audience, scores higher in practice than the raw numbers suggest.","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775057728512}}
