{"type":"message","id":"03f54b20","parentId":"bde63ec7","timestamp":"2026-04-01T15:39:17.744Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_2e821ae3-8c23-49b6-a30f-96bfb03806b5","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag/drafts/li026_linkedin.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":25646,"output":340,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":25986,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775057957743}}
{"type":"message","id":"a607c39b","parentId":"03f54b20","timestamp":"2026-04-01T15:39:17.766Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_2e821ae3-8c23-49b6-a30f-96bfb03806b5","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# LI026 — EB-3 vs TN: The False Choice (LinkedIn Post)\n\n---\n\nYour travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks.\n\nMeanwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still arguing about EB-3 versus TN like you can only pick one.\n\nStop.\n\nEB-3 is a permanence play. Three years minimum before the math works. TN is a speed play. Two to six months before your candidate is on unit. The moment you treat those as competitors, you've already lost the staffing conversation you should be having.\n\nHere is what the comparison actually looks like when you run it honestly.\n\nTN all-in runs $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 runs $25,000 to $35,000. On the surface, TN wins. Except surface is where CFOs die. Run the same math to three years — and that is the minimum horizon for EB-3 to break even — and the EB-3 number flattens against the accumulated travel nurse premiums you avoided. One open req that stays unfilled for six months costs you $40,000 to $80,000 in overtime, PRN spreads, and agency premiums. That is not a footnote. That is the entire EB-3 cost argument.\n\n**The facilities getting this right are not choosing.** They are running both tracks. TN candidates for the positions that need to be filled now. EB-3 candidates for the staffing base the unit actually needs three years from now. Different pipelines. Different timelines. Same workforce plan.\n\n**The April 2026 visa bulletin just made the EB-3 ROW decision faster.** Dates for Filing = Current for Rest of World. That means approvals clearing in 2026 that people expected to wait until late 2027 for. Facilities sitting on outdated \"EB-3 takes forever\" assumptions are leaving their own staffing plans unspoken for.\n\nAnd if a candidate is born in the Philippines or Mexico instead of India? The timeline compression is even sharper.\n\nThe India-born EB-3 reality is a different conversation. Priority dates still stuck in 2012 or 2013. Five to seven years minimum. Structural attrition that nobody talks about honestly — a cohort of four India-born EB-3 candidates typically yields one permanent hire after four to five years. If you are sponsoring India-born nurses, you need to have that conversation early and clearly.\n\n**The question is not EB-3 or TN.** The question is what your staffing situation actually demands, and whether you are building infrastructure or just filling gaps.\n\nYou do not have to choose.\n\n---\n\nNava Healthcare runs both tracks. We have for years. If you want to see what parallel track infrastructure actually looks like for your facility, we can walk through it. No commitment required. Just the math."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":9,"aggregated":"# LI026 — EB-3 vs TN: The False Choice (LinkedIn Post)\n\n---\n\nYour travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks.\n\nMeanwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still arguing about EB-3 versus TN like you can only pick one.\n\nStop.\n\nEB-3 is a permanence play. Three years minimum before the math works. TN is a speed play. Two to six months before your candidate is on unit. The moment you treat those as competitors, you've already lost the staffing conversation you should be having.\n\nHere is what the comparison actually looks like when you run it honestly.\n\nTN all-in runs $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 runs $25,000 to $35,000. On the surface, TN wins. Except surface is where CFOs die. Run the same math to three years — and that is the minimum horizon for EB-3 to break even — and the EB-3 number flattens against the accumulated travel nurse premiums you avoided. One open req that stays unfilled for six months costs you $40,000 to $80,000 in overtime, PRN spreads, and agency premiums. That is not a footnote. That is the entire EB-3 cost argument.\n\n**The facilities getting this right are not choosing.** They are running both tracks. TN candidates for the positions that need to be filled now. EB-3 candidates for the staffing base the unit actually needs three years from now. Different pipelines. Different timelines. Same workforce plan.\n\n**The April 2026 visa bulletin just made the EB-3 ROW decision faster.** Dates for Filing = Current for Rest of World. That means approvals clearing in 2026 that people expected to wait until late 2027 for. Facilities sitting on outdated \"EB-3 takes forever\" assumptions are leaving their own staffing plans unspoken for.\n\nAnd if a candidate is born in the Philippines or Mexico instead of India? The timeline compression is even sharper.\n\nThe India-born EB-3 reality is a different conversation. Priority dates still stuck in 2012 or 2013. Five to seven years minimum. Structural attrition that nobody talks about honestly — a cohort of four India-born EB-3 candidates typically yields one permanent hire after four to five years. If you are sponsoring India-born nurses, you need to have that conversation early and clearly.\n\n**The question is not EB-3 or TN.** The question is what your staffing situation actually demands, and whether you are building infrastructure or just filling gaps.\n\nYou do not have to choose.\n\n---\n\nNava Healthcare runs both tracks. We have for years. If you want to see what parallel track infrastructure actually looks like for your facility, we can walk through it. No commitment required. Just the math.","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775057957760}}
