{"type":"message","id":"13e4abcb","parentId":"94253534","timestamp":"2026-04-01T15:58:24.746Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both score identically on TinyQE — same two mechanical errors, same structural complaints. The tool isn't picking up the qualitative difference because it's built for format detection, not editorial comparison.\n\nHere's the real comparison:\n\n**V1 (original):** More structured, more citations, more comprehensive. Has meta-title, meta-description, key takeaways box, inline source links, a sources section. Heavier, more reference-material feel. Four main sections with sub-headings. Closer to a white paper.\n\n**V2 (Draft v2):** Leaner, more direct, better rhythm. Opens harder (\"Your travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks\"). The five variables get more airtime and clearer explanations. Blockquotes break up the density. Better for a LinkedIn audience — it argues, not just explains.\n\n**My read:** V2 is the stronger blog draft. It's tighter, the voice is more consistent, and the \"you're asking the wrong question\" framing lands cleaner than V1's more academic approach.\n\n**However — V2 has one material issue:** It cuts the \"2026 Forecast\" section entirely and replaces it with a different structure. That section contains the visa bulletin news (April 2026, EB-3 ROW \"Dates for Filing = Current\") which is time-sensitive and valuable. V1 has it; V2 mentions it but buries it in the recapture pool paragraph without the bulletin context.\n\n**Recommendation:** V2 as the base, but graft the 2026 Forecast section from V1 into it. That gives you the tight narrative of V2 with the regulatory currency of V1.\n\nWant me to do that merge, or do you want to work through it yourself?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":37252,"output":413,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":37665,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775059104743}}
