{"type":"message","id":"dcb64662","parentId":"a916ddab","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:10:53.902Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You're right to call this out. Let me diagnose what happened.\n\n**What I did:**\nWhen the merge task came in, I read the LinkedIn writer skill — because it was in my workspace skills folder and I grabbed it reflexively, without asking whether it was the right tool for the job.\n\n**Why it's wrong:**\nA blog article is not a LinkedIn post. The LinkedIn writer skill has constraints that don't apply here — 1300-character limits, max 1-2 bold instances, platform-specific formatting rules. Those are for social posts, not long-form blog content. I was applying the wrong framework to the wrong format.\n\n**What I should have done instead:**\n1. **Editor skill** — for structural and editorial guidance on the article itself\n2. **NavaAA agent** — for passing the merged content through the Nava voice filter\n\nI did the editorial passes manually (which produced V3, and the content is better for it), but I should have run NavaAA passes as you requested — \"run them past TinyQE and I will work on finalizing them\" meant I should have also passed them through NavaAA, not just TinyQE.\n\n**Skills I should have used for this task:**\n- `editor` skill — structural/editorial\n- NavaAA agent (when built) — voice/alignment\n- TinyQE — quality evaluation\n- NOT `linkedin-writer` — wrong format\n\nThe merge result (V3) is solid, but the process was sloppy. I defaulted to the nearest skill in my folder instead of thinking about which tool actually fits the job. That needs to change."}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":41962,"output":566,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42528,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775059853901}}
