nwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still treating EB-3 and TN as if you can only pick one. They are not the same menu.\n\n**The right visa pathway is the one that matches your actual staffing situation --- and most facilities need both.**\n\nEB-3 is a permanence play. Three years minimum before the investment math works. TN is a speed play. Two to six months before your candidate is on unit. The moment you treat those as competitors, you have already lost the staffing conversation yo...\n- Assistant: Now let me run both through TinyQE.\n[non-text content: toolCall]\n- Tool result (exec): TinyQE Assessment — Generic\n\nOverall: Needs Work. Content shows promise but requires significant improvement.\n\nTop 3 Priorities:\n1. Linguistic Integrity (severity: high | weight: 8%) — 2 mechanical errors detected. Highest priority: missing space after period\n   → Address errors in order: missing space after period, missing space after period\n2. Thesis Clarity (severity: high | weight: 8%) — No clear thesis detected.\n   → State your central claim clearly in the opening paragraph.\n3. Structural Completeness (severity: high | weight: 8%) — Structure is incomplete. Missing: CLAIM, EVIDENCE, RESOL...\n- Assistant: [non-text content: toolCall]\n- Tool result (exec): TinyQE Assessment — Generic\n\nOverall: Needs Work. Content shows promise but requires significant improvement.\n\nTop 3 Priorities:\n1. Linguistic Integrity (severity: high | weight: 8%) — 2 mechanical errors detected. Highest priority: missing space after period\n   → Address errors in order: missing space after period, missing space after period\n2. Thesis Clarity (severity: high | weight: 8%) — No clear thesis detected.\n   → State your central claim clearly in the opening paragraph.\n3. Structural Completeness (severity: high | weight: 8%) — Structure is incomplete. Missing: CLAIM, EVIDENCE, RESOL...\n- Assistant: Both score identically on TinyQE — same two mechanical errors, same structural complaints. The tool isn't picking up the qualitative difference because it's built for format detection, not editorial comparison.\n\nHere's the real comparison:\n\n**V1 (original):** More structured, more citations, more comprehensive. Has meta-title, meta-description, key takeaways box, inline source links, a sources section. Heavier, more reference-material feel. Four main sections with sub-headings. Closer to a white paper.\n\n**V2 (Draft v2):** Leaner, more direct, better rhythm. Opens harder (\"Your travel nurse inv...","firstKeptEntryId":"a916ddab","tokensBefore":42528,"fromHook":true}
