{"type":"message","id":"5551d40d","parentId":"83517696","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:17:52.980Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now the editorial passes. Let me analyze the full document systematically.\n\n**PASS 1 — STRUCTURE AUDIT:**\n\nH2 sections: ✅ All have contextualizing intros  \nH2 blockquotes: ✅ All present  \nH3 sections: ❌ No H3s — this is a Statement of Trade, not a blog-style article. The structure is linear prose, not H2→H3 hierarchy. Acceptable for SoT format.  \nEm-dashes: ✅ Only 1 (line 5, inside bold) — acceptable  \nBold in body: ⚠️ Line 5 bold is a section-intro pivot (not a heading) — borderline but functional  \nNo \"trap\" language: ✅  \nNo strawmen: ✅ — genuinely acknowledges both pathways fairly  \nKillshot idiom: ✅ \"Nice dream. But impractical.\" not used — actually correct here (文章 doesn't kill a hypothetical, it resolves a binary)  \nAI vocabulary: ✅ clean  \nWord repetition: Let me check —\n\n**PASS 2 — VOICE AUDIT:**\n\nThe voice is already strong. The \"em-dash in bold\" on line 5 is the only formatting concern — it's functioning as a section pivot, not a heading, which is borderline acceptable. Let me fix it by restructuring that line.\n\n**PASS 3 — DEPTH + EVIDENCE:**\n\nThe TinyQE flagged \"evidence quality\" and \"structural completeness.\" The evidence is actually present ($40K-$80K vacancy cost, 200-bed facility example, 4-nurse case study) but it can be sharpened. The 4-nurse case study is good but buried. Let me strengthen the evidence framing inline.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_db9524d0-9f22-4569-9bbb-d6b8ba55c229","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"The right visa pathway is the one that matches your actual staffing situation. Most facilities need both.\n\nEB-3 is a permanence play.","old_string":"**The right visa pathway is the one that matches your actual staffing situation — and most facilities need both.**\n\nEB-3 is a permanence play.","path":"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Down