,"output":631,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39256,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775060340216}}
{"type":"message","id":"aa7d055b","parentId":"ae21ed64","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:19:00.267Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_b5a44c41-3013-4a3f-b3f5-e476845d71a2","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md."}],"details":{"diff":"    ...\n 43 ## 2026 Forecast: Reading the Bulletin Without a Law Degree\n 44 \n 45 The State Department visa bulletin for April 2026 sent a signal that immigration practitioners are still parsing, and it matters directly to healthcare staffing planners. For EB-3 Rest of World, the designation moved to \"Dates for Filing = Current,\" which means foreign labor certification approvals can be filed immediately against the current fiscal year without waiting for a priority date to become current. For facilities that have EB-3 cases in flight for non-India candidates, this is the fastest forward motion the bulletin has shown in years. Approvals that were expected to clear in late 2027 may now clear in 2026. That is a material difference in cash flow timing for a facility that has been paying recruiting costs against an uncertain arrival date.\n 46 \n-47 The India EB-3 situation continues to operate under a different reality entirely. The priority date for India-born EB-3 applicants remains stuck at 2012 or 2013, which means the queue for those candidates is not moving in any practical sense. The story that illustrates this better than any policy brief is the 2019 Midwest LTC facility that sponsored four international nurses through the EB-3 process simultaneously. Three of the four candidates withdrew from the process over the following four years, worn down by the uncertainty and the extended timeline. One nurse received her green card in 2023. The facility, which had budgeted for four permanent hires, ended up with one. That is not a processing delay. That is attrition, and it is the structural risk that makes the India-born EB-3 pathway something that requires frank conversation with candidates before commitment.\n+47 India-born EB-3 applicants remain stuck at a 2012 or 2013 priority date, which means the queue is not moving in any practical sense. The story that illustrates this better than any policy brief: a 2019 Midwest LTC facility sponsored four international nurses through EB-3 simultaneously. Three of the four withdrew over the following four years, worn down by the uncertainty. One nurse received her green card in 2023. The facility ended up with one permanent hire instead of four. That is not a processing delay. That is attrition, and it is the structural risk that makes India-born EB-3 something that requires frank conversation with candidates before commitment.\n 48 \n 49 Geography remains the single most deterministic variable in the entire immigration planning equation. A candidate born in the Philippines moves faster through the EB-3 queue than one born in India, purely as a function of demand and backlog. Rest of World candidates, which includes most of the global nursing talent pool outside India and China, are now moving faster than they have in the prior five-year window. Facilities that are treating EB-3 as uniformly slow are operating on outdated information. The correct frame for 2026 is: it depends entirely on the candidate's country of birth.\n 50 \n 51 The [Healthcare Workforce Resilience Act](https://navahc.com/fix-your-flexible-staffing-model-in-healthcare/) has opened a secondary pathway that staffing planners should be tracking. The recaptured pool includes approximately 25,000 nursing slots from previously approved immigrant petitions that were never utilized. Facilities that are monitoring their visa bulletin position carefully may find that candidates caught in the recaptured pool can be advanced faster than the standard queue would suggest. This is not a guarantee and it is not uniformly distributed, but the bulletin movement suggests the recapture mechanism is active and functioning for healthcare categories.\n    ...","firstChangedLine":47},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775060340259}}
{"type":"message","id":"c39ce95c","parentId":"aa7d055b","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:19:07.832Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_c91ae433-7509-4822-bc05-10aa2e65f449","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"The parallel track approach resolves this tension entirely. Run TN for positions that need to be filled in the next six months. Run EB-3 for the permanent staffing base the facility needs to build over the next three years. These are not competing pipelines. They are separate pipelines serving different strategic objectives within the same staffing plan. A 200-bed LTC facility running both tracks might have 12 TN nurses on unit at any given time, covering rotational gaps, while simultaneously building a permanent core of 20 EB-3 nurses who arrived over the past two years and will be there for the next decade.","old_string":"The parallel track approach resolves this tension entirely. Run TN for the positions that need to be filled in the next six months, and run EB-3 for the permanent staffing base the facility needs to build over the next three years. These are not competing pipelines. They are separate pipelines serving different strategic objectives within the same facility. A 200-bed LTC facility running both tracks might have 12 TN nurses on unit at any given time, covering the rotational gaps, while simultaneously building a permanent core of 20 EB-3 nurses who arrived over the past two years and will be there for the next decade.","path":"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":39029,"output":329,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39358,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775060347832}}
{"type":"message","id":"36422cdb","parentId":"c39ce95c","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:19:07.873Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_c91ae433-7509-4822-bc05-10aa2e65f449","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md."}],"details":{"diff":"    ...\n 33 Here is the number set that most facilities never see in one place. TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate, with arrival timelines of two to six months from the start of the process. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000 per candidate, with a minimum commitment horizon of three years before the investment fully breaks even. On the surface, EB-3 looks expensive. That surface reading is where most CFOs stop, and that is where the analysis gets dangerous.\n 34 \n 35 What does an open req actually cost while the position sits empty? A single open registered nurse position, unfilled for six months, typically generates $40,000 to $80,000 in accumulated costs through overtime, PRN premiums, and agency premiums. Multiply that across five or ten open reqs, which is not unusual for a mid-sized LTC facility, and the vacancy cost during an EB-3 wait [easily reaches $200,000 to $400,000](https://navahc.com/fix-your-flexible-staffing-model-in-healthcare/). The $25,000 to $35,000 EB-3 investment starts looking competitive against that math, but only if the facility actually stays the course for the full three-year term. Facilities that abandon EB-3 halfway through and switch to travel nurses end up with the worst of both worlds: the EB-3 sunk cost plus the ongoing agency premium, with nothing to show for either.\n 36 \n-37 The parallel track approach resolves this tension entirely. Run TN for the positions that need to be filled in the next six months, and run EB-3 for the permanent staffing base the facility needs to build over the next three years. These are not competing pipelines. They are separate pipelines serving different strategic objectives within the same facility. A 200-bed LTC facility running both tracks might have 12 TN nurses on unit at any given time, covering the rotational gaps, while simultaneously building a permanent core of 20 EB-3 nurses who arrived over the past two years and will be there for the next decade.\n+37 The parallel track approach resolves this tension entirely. Run TN for positions that need to be filled in the next six months. Run EB-3 for the permanent staffing base the facility needs to build over the next three years. These are not competing pipelines. They are separate pipelines serving different strategic objectives within the same staffing plan. A 200-bed LTC facility running both tracks might have 12 TN nurses on unit at any given time, covering rotational gaps, while simultaneously building a permanent core of 20 EB-3 nurses who arrived over the past two years and will be there for the next decade.\n 38 \n 39 The cost comparison only favors TN when the time horizon is short. EB-3 wins on permanence and long-term cost per registered nurse per year. The facility that runs both tracks intelligently is not choosing between two options. It is building a staffing infrastructure that covers both the immediate and the structural.\n 40 \n 41 > The math only favors TN if you stop running it after six months. Run it to three years and the numbers tell a different story.\n    ...","firstChangedLine":37},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775060347864}}
{"type":"message","id":"ad9fb077","parentId":"36422cdb","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:19:17.199Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now fix the dense \"that\" paragraph in the EB-3 section:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_8eccc28e-0cb4-45ff-b4a4-544d0bf9e352","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"EB-3 is the right answer when permanence is the objective. When a facility is building a long-term staffing base rather than filling a temporary gap, EB-3 candidates who arrive as green card holders are structurally committed in a way that no temporary work authorization can replicate. The retention data on EB-3 international nurses consistently outperforms domestic new hires over a three-year horizon, primarily because the investment required from both sides creates mutual accountability. Large cohorts of 10 or more nurses moving through the EB-3 pipeline simultaneously generate the critical mass needed to shift unit culture in a lasting direction. [Facilities that have made the three-year commitment and stayed the course](https://navahc.com/the-anatomy-of-a-clinician-turnover/) are the ones reporting the highest satisfaction with the international recruitment model. The key phrase is \"stayed the course.\"","old_string":"EB-3 is the right answer when permanence is the objective. When a facility is building a long-term staffing base rather than filling a temporary gap, EB-3 candidates who arrive as green card holders are structurally committed in a way that no temporary work authorization can replicate. The retention data on EB-3 international nurses consistently outperforms domestic new hires over a three-year horizon, primarily because the investment required from both sides creates mutual accountability. Large cohorts of 10 or more nurses moving through the EB-3 pipeline simultaneously generate the critical mass needed to shift unit culture in a lasting direction. [Facilities that have made the three-year commitment and stayed the course](https://navahc.com/the-anatomy-of-a-clinician-turnover/) are the ones reporting the highest satisfaction with the international recruitment model. The key phrase is \"stayed the course.\"","path":"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":39368,"output":484,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39852,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775060357198}}
