{"type":"message","id":"f6c36469","parentId":"f6ad0a6c","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:33:40.739Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have the specific violations. Let me list them clearly before fixing:\n\n### VIOLATIONS FOUND\n\n1. **Paragraph Density Violation**: Para 2 has exactly 3 sentences: \"Your travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks. Meanwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still treating EB-3 and TN as if you can only pick one. They are not the same menu.\" — violates \"Never write exactly 3 sentences.\"\n\n2. **Bold in Body Violation**: Line 5: \"**The right visa pathway is the one that matches your actual staffing situation.**\" — bold used for section-intro pivot, not a heading. Violates \"No Bold in Body\" (bold only for headings and blockquotes).\n\n3. **Missing H2 Introductions (Technical)**: While all H2s have intro paragraphs, the editor skill expects H3s beneath them. Since this is an SoT (not blog), the H2→H3 structure doesn't apply. *I'll note this as format-appropriate, not a violation.*\n\n4. **Missing Transition Words**: Multiple paragraphs start without transition words (e.g., Para 3 starts with \"The\", Para 4 with \"EB-3\", Para 5 with \"In\"). Violates Bridge Protocol: \"Every paragraph leads with a transition word that signals logical connection to the previous idea.\"\n\nLet me fix these two clear violations first:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_b479cb79-aaca-40b5-9b56-c522768d416e","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"Your travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks. Meanwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still treating EB-3 and TN as if you can only pick one. They are not the same menu. This false binary obscures the real strategic question: which pathway matches your actual staffing situation?","old_string":"Your travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks. Meanwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still treating EB-3 and TN as if you can only pick one. They are not the same menu.\n\nThe right visa pathway is the one that matches your actual staffing situation. Most facilities need both.","path":"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"nemotron-3-super:cloud","usage":{"input":56661,"output":473,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":57134,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775061220738}}
{"type":"message","id":"e5aefe41","parentId":"f6c36469","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:33:40.789Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_b479cb79-aaca-40b5-9b56-c522768d416e","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md."}],"details":{"diff":"  1 # Which Visa Pathway Is Right for Your Facility: EB-3 or TN?\n  2 \n- 3 Your travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks. Meanwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still treating EB-3 and TN as if you can only pick one. They are not the same menu.\n+ 3 Your travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks. Meanwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still treating EB-3 and TN as if you can only pick one. They are not the same menu. This false binary obscures the real strategic question: which pathway matches your actual staffing situation?\n  4 \n- 5 The right visa pathway is the one that matches your actual staffing situation. Most facilities need both.\n- 6 \n  7 EB-3 is a permanence play. Three years minimum before the investment math works. TN is a speed play. Two to six months before your candidate is on unit. The moment you treat those as competitors, you have already lost the staffing conversation you should be having.\n  8 \n  9 In most cases, the answer is not one or the other. It is both.\n 10 \n    ...","firstChangedLine":3},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775061220782}}
