{"type":"message","id":"9df0cc7f","parentId":"c6a45558","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:33:49.804Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me check the exact current text around that area:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_55300393-bdad-4050-bf95-d23a3415a779","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md","offset":1,"limit":10}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"nemotron-3-super:cloud","usage":{"input":57387,"output":75,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":57462,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775061229803}}
{"type":"message","id":"081b16b2","parentId":"9df0cc7f","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:33:49.840Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_55300393-bdad-4050-bf95-d23a3415a779","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Which Visa Pathway Is Right for Your Facility: EB-3 or TN?\n\nYour travel nurse invoice arrives every 13 weeks. Meanwhile, someone in your HR meeting is still treating EB-3 and TN as if you can only pick one. They are not the same menu. This false binary obscures the real strategic question: which pathway matches your actual staffing situation?\n\nEB-3 is a permanence play. Three years minimum before the investment math works. TN is a speed play. Two to six months before your candidate is on unit. The moment you treat those as competitors, you have already lost the staffing conversation you should be having.\n\nIn most cases, the answer is not one or the other. It is both.\n\n## You're Asking the Wrong Question\n\n\n[58 more lines in file. Use offset=11 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775061229830}}
{"type":"message","id":"8a229fad","parentId":"081b16b2","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:33:55.291Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I see — the bold is already gone from that area (I removed it earlier). The current line 5 is: \"EB-3 is a permanence play.\" — no bold. Let me double-check if there's any bold left in the body:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_52c2b99c-6176-4cd8-bca1-d7bcd0fb8fe9","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"\\*\\*\" /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa\\ Pathway\\ Comparison\\ v3.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"nemotron-3-super:cloud","usage":{"input":57653,"output":103,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":57756,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775061235290}}
{"type":"message","id":"3fb4a407","parentId":"8a229fad","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:33:55.338Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_52c2b99c-6176-4cd8-bca1-d7bcd0fb8fe9","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"15:**Vacancy urgency.** If the position needs to be filled within six months, TN is the only realistic option. EB-3 timelines, even under the best conditions, run years. A facility in crisis mode does not have the luxury of a pipeline built for permanence.\n17:**Budget reality.** TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000. The delta is real and it matters. But the comparison is incomplete without factoring in what an open req costs each month of the wait.\n19:**Commitment horizon.** EB-3 only makes financial sense if the facility is prepared to employ the nurse for the full three-year term minimum. Anything shorter means the investment never breaks even. If the facility has a history of restructuring or layoffs, the permanence argument collapses.\n21:**Candidate origin.** TN is restricted to Canadian and Mexican nationals under the USMCA framework. EB-3 draws from the global pool. If a facility needs a specific nationality profile, or if the candidate pool in Canada or Mexico happens to match your needs, TN has a geographic advantage. If not, TN is simply not an option.\n23:**Retention objective.** Non-immigrant intent is the structural ceiling on TN retention. The moment a TN nurse starts thinking about their next career move, the incentive structure that kept them committed to a facility evaporates. EB-3 permanence aligns the nurse's legal status with their professional future."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":19,"aggregated":"15:**Vacancy urgency.** If the position needs to be filled within six months, TN is the only realistic option. EB-3 timelines, even under the best conditions, run years. A facility in crisis mode does not have the luxury of a pipeline built for permanence.\n17:**Budget reality.** TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000. The delta is real and it matters. But the comparison is incomplete without factoring in what an open req costs each month of the wait.\n19:**Commitment horizon.** EB-3 only makes financial sense if the facility is prepared to employ the nurse for the full three-year term minimum. Anything shorter means the investment never breaks even. If the facility has a history of restructuring or layoffs, the permanence argument collapses.\n21:**Candidate origin.** TN is restricted to Canadian and Mexican nationals under the USMCA framework. EB-3 draws from the global pool. If a facility needs a specific nationality profile, or if the candidate pool in Canada or Mexico happens to match your needs, TN has a geographic advantage. If not, TN is simply not an option.\n23:**Retention objective.** Non-immigrant intent is the structural ceiling on TN retention. The moment a TN nurse starts thinking about their next career move, the incentive structure that kept them committed to a facility evaporates. EB-3 permanence aligns the nurse's legal status with their professional future.","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775061235332}}
{"type":"message","id":"e955aa69","parentId":"3fb4a407","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:34:03.499Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Ah — the bold is being used as subsection labels within the H2 sections (\"Vacancy urgency.\", \"Budget reality.\", etc.). This violates the \"No Bold in Body\" rule — bold is only for headings (H1, H2, H3) and blockquote callouts.\n\nLet me fix those:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_306fa66e-3f31-4ba8-b1b3-7fb64932c88b","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"Vacancy urgency. If the position needs to be filled within six months, TN is the only realistic option. EB-3 timelines, even under the best conditions, run years. A facility in crisis mode does not have the luxury of a pipeline built for permanence.","old_string":"**Vacancy urgency.** If the position needs to be filled within six months, TN is the only realistic option. EB-3 timelines, even under the best conditions, run years. A facility in crisis mode does not have the luxury of a pipeline built for permanence.","path":"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"nemotron-3-super:cloud","usage":{"input":58100,"output":237,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":58337,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775061243499}}
{"type":"message","id":"132c2736","parentId":"e955aa69","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:34:03.547Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_306fa66e-3f31-4ba8-b1b3-7fb64932c88b","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md."}],"details":{"diff":"    ...\n 11 The binary framing of EB-3 versus TN has always been a distraction. It treats two fundamentally different immigration mechanisms as if they were competing options on the same menu, when in reality they answer different strategic questions. EB-3 is a permanent residency pathway. TN is a temporary work authorization mechanism. [Treating them as equivalents is like comparing a mortgage to a hotel reservation](https://navahc.com/the-anatomy-of-a-clinician-turnover/) and asking which is better. The answer depends entirely on whether you are trying to build something permanent or bridge something immediate.\n 12 \n 13 There are five variables that actually determine which pathway fits a facility. Most leaders have never seen all five laid out at once, and none of them work in isolation.\n 14 \n-15 **Vacancy urgency.** If the position needs to be filled within six months, TN is the only realistic option. EB-3 timelines, even under the best conditions, run years. A facility in crisis mode does not have the luxury of a pipeline built for permanence.\n+15 Vacancy urgency. If the position needs to be filled within six months, TN is the only realistic option. EB-3 timelines, even under the best conditions, run years. A facility in crisis mode does not have the luxury of a pipeline built for permanence.\n 16 \n 17 **Budget reality.** TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000. The delta is real and it matters. But the comparison is incomplete without factoring in what an open req costs each month of the wait.\n 18 \n 19 **Commitment horizon.** EB-3 only makes financial sense if the facility is prepared to employ the nurse for the full three-year term minimum. Anything shorter means the investment never breaks even. If the facility has a history of restructuring or layoffs, the permanence argument collapses.\n    ...","firstChangedLine":15},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775061243538}}
{"type":"message","id":"10c7da5a","parentId":"132c2736","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:34:13.785Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_c0b993e4-5633-4310-83b1-56eb9b88fcfb","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"Budget reality. TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000. The delta is real and it matters. But the comparison is incomplete without factoring in what an open req costs each month of the wait.","old_string":"**Budget reality.** TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000. The delta is real and it matters. But the comparison is incomplete without factoring in what an open req costs each month of the wait.","path":"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"nemotron-3-super:cloud","usage":{"input":58379,"output":213,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":58592,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775061253785}}
{"type":"message","id":"c169b005","parentId":"10c7da5a","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:34:13.824Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_c0b993e4-5633-4310-83b1-56eb9b88fcfb","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md."}],"details":{"diff":"    ...\n 13 There are five variables that actually determine which pathway fits a facility. Most leaders have never seen all five laid out at once, and none of them work in isolation.\n 14 \n 15 Vacancy urgency. If the position needs to be filled within six months, TN is the only realistic option. EB-3 timelines, even under the best conditions, run years. A facility in crisis mode does not have the luxury of a pipeline built for permanence.\n 16 \n-17 **Budget reality.** TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000. The delta is real and it matters. But the comparison is incomplete without factoring in what an open req costs each month of the wait.\n+17 Budget reality. TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000. The delta is real and it matters. But the comparison is incomplete without factoring in what an open req costs each month of the wait.\n 18 \n 19 **Commitment horizon.** EB-3 only makes financial sense if the facility is prepared to employ the nurse for the full three-year term minimum. Anything shorter means the investment never breaks even. If the facility has a history of restructuring or layoffs, the permanence argument collapses.\n 20 \n 21 **Candidate origin.** TN is restricted to Canadian and Mexican nationals under the USMCA framework. EB-3 draws from the global pool. If a facility needs a specific nationality profile, or if the candidate pool in Canada or Mexico happens to match your needs, TN has a geographic advantage. If not, TN is simply not an option.\n    ...","firstChangedLine":17},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775061253813}}
{"type":"message","id":"5858173e","parentId":"c169b005","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:34:18.541Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_e12d681d-6843-4c6b-894a-471b2443ff98","name":"edit","arguments":{"new_string":"Commitment horizon. EB-3 only makes financial sense if the facility is prepared to employ the nurse for the full three-year term minimum. Anything shorter means the investment never breaks even. If the facility has a history of restructuring or layoffs, the permanence argument collapses.","old_string":"**Commitment horizon.** EB-3 only makes financial sense if the facility is prepared to employ the nurse for the full three-year term minimum. Anything shorter means the investment never breaks even. If the facility has a history of restructuring or layoffs, the permanence argument collapses.","path":"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"nemotron-3-super:cloud","usage":{"input":58635,"output":172,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":58807,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775061258541}}
{"type":"message","id":"40b4c83d","parentId":"5858173e","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:34:18.596Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_e12d681d-6843-4c6b-894a-471b2443ff98","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md."}],"details":{"diff":"    ...\n 15 Vacancy urgency. If the position needs to be filled within six months, TN is the only realistic option. EB-3 timelines, even under the best conditions, run years. A facility in crisis mode does not have the luxury of a pipeline built for permanence.\n 16 \n 17 Budget reality. TN all-in costs run $7,000 to $15,000 per candidate. EB-3 all-in costs run $25,000 to $35,000. The delta is real and it matters. But the comparison is incomplete without factoring in what an open req costs each month of the wait.\n 18 \n-19 **Commitment horizon.** EB-3 only makes financial sense if the facility is prepared to employ the nurse for the full three-year term minimum. Anything shorter means the investment never breaks even. If the facility has a history of restructuring or layoffs, the permanence argument collapses.\n+19 Commitment horizon. EB-3 only makes financial sense if the facility is prepared to employ the nurse for the full three-year term minimum. Anything shorter means the investment never breaks even. If the facility has a history of restructuring or layoffs, the permanence argument collapses.\n 20 \n 21 **Candidate origin.** TN is restricted to Canadian and Mexican nationals under the USMCA framework. EB-3 draws from the global pool. If a facility needs a specific nationality profile, or if the candidate pool in Canada or Mexico happens to match your needs, TN has a geographic advantage. If not, TN is simply not an option.\n 22 \n 23 **Retention objective.** Non-immigrant intent is the structural ceiling on TN retention. The moment a TN nurse starts thinking about their next career move, the incentive structure that kept them committed to a facility evaporates. EB-3 permanence aligns the nurse's legal status with their professional future.\n    ...","firstChangedLine":19},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775061258583}}
