r depends entirely on whether you are trying to build something permanent or bridge something im...\n- Assistant: Let me add transition words to improve the flow. I'll start with the H2 section intros and key transition points:\n[non-text content: toolCall]\n- Tool result (edit): Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md.\n- Assistant: [non-text content: toolCall]\n- Tool result (edit): Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md.\n- Assistant: Now let me work on the \"The Math You've Never Seen Laid Out\" section:\n[non-text content: toolCall]\n- Tool result (read): ## 2026 Forecast: Reading the Bulletin Without a Law Degree\n\nThe State Department visa bulletin for April 2026 sent a signal that immigration practitioners are still parsing, and it matters directly to healthcare staffing planners. For EB-3 Rest of World, the designation moved to \"Dates for Filing = Current,\" which means foreign labor certification approvals can be filed immediately against the current fiscal year without waiting for a priority date to become current. For facilities that have EB-3 cases in flight for non-India candidates, this is the fastest forward motion the bulletin has sho...\n- Assistant: Let me add a transition to the 2026 Forecast section:\n[non-text content: toolCall]\n- Tool result (edit): Successfully replaced text in /mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/Visa Pathway Comparison v3.md.\n- Assistant: Now let me check the final section and add transitions where needed:\n[non-text content: toolCall]\n- Tool result (read): TN is the right answer when speed is the governing variable. When a facility needs a candidate on unit within six months, or when the target population happens to be Canadian or Mexican nationals who qualify under USMCA, TN delivers where EB-3 cannot. TN also serves as an effective pressure valve for facilities that are in a genuine staffing crisis and cannot affor